To solve these issues, we herein develop a novel fluorescent sensing platform based on the nanocomposite consisting of a Zr-based MOF, UiO-66-NH2, and a fluorescent dye, rhodamine B (RhB). This nanocomposite (denoted as RhB@UiO-66-NH2) can be easily constructed by direct adsorption of RhB into the architecture of UiO-66-NH2. UiO-66-NH2, as the working fluorescence center, showed a good response to phosphate because of high affinity between phosphate and the Zr-O node in UiO-66-NH2 
                     [33], which weakened the ligand-to-metal charge transfer (LMCT) process and eventually recovered the fluorescence of the ligand 2-aminoterephthalic acid (ATA) [29]. Besides, since it did not interact with phosphate, RhB can serve as an internal reference fluorescence center to endow the fluorescent nanoprobe with self-calibrating capacity to well circumvent the environmental interference. Thus, accurate, sensitive and selective detection of phosphate is readily achieved (see Scheme 1
                     ). RhB@UiO-66-NH2 is also demonstrated to be potential as a recyclable sensor for phosphate with the stripping agent Eu3+ ions based on the stronger binding ability of phosphate with Eu3+ than with the Zr-O node [15–17]. More importantly, we first report the use of agarose hydrogels as the matrix to immobilize RhB@UiO-66-NH2 to afford a robust solid sensing platform, with which the detection procedure for phosphate could be simply accomplished by only soaking into human serum, and accordingly signal readout would be observed by visual fluorescence color change. Thereby, this smart MOF nanocomposite immobilized hydrogels may provide a straightforward fashion to enable quantification and visualization of phosphate for on-site clinical analysis due to free instrumentation and operational simplicity.
